</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uillandraazuryne.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Illandra Azuryne</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(10/25/01 9:41:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovefrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=127.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Lvl 15 (epic?) Ring of Nature Affinity</span><hr size=1> As other have said, it adds to your casting level.  All the ways that this affects how spells are cast is not completely known, other than that it generally makes them better.<br>
<br>
Take this example, <br>
<br>
  11 &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Major Regeneration &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Heals 99 HP <br>
<br>
(Based on information from Allakhazams)<br>
<br>
If you were a pure regrowth specialist, when you first get this spell at 11, you would notice it healing for 123 hps of damage (like it does for me most of the time).  This is basically 125% of the base healing value.  If at this point you switched and started specializing in Nurture, as you advanced in levels, you would eventually start to notice that it started to heal less than 123 hps.  This would start to happen when your specialization level starts to drop below 2/3rds of your actual level.  Having an item that increases your apparent specialization level will allow you to continue to cast for max longer.<br>
<br>
Illandra Azuryne<br>
Level 58 Paladin - Xegony<br>
Level 21 Druid - Gawaine<br>
